{"title_page": "Zygogynum howeanum", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Glossy leaf tree Lord Howe Island.jpg\n| status = \n| status_system = \n| genus = Zygogynum\n| species = howeanum\n| authority = ([[Ferdinand von Mueller|F.Muell.]]) [[Willem Vink|Vink]]\n}}\n\n'''''Zygogynum howeanum''''', commonly known as '''hotbark''' or '''hot bark''', is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Winteraceae]].  It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]]\u2019s [[subtropical]] [[Lord Howe Island]] in the [[Tasman Sea]].  The specific [[epithet]] refers to the locality.\n\n==Description==\nHotbark is a tree that grows to 13&nbsp;m in height.  It has a dark, smooth trunk. Its large, bluntly pointed leaves are dark green on the upper surface and paler beneath.  The white flowers are 20&nbsp;mm in diameter, flowering from June to December, and are insect-pollinated.  The fruit is a round black berry, 8&nbsp;mm across, containing 5\u201315 small seeds.<ref name=lhibmp>{{cite book |title=Appendices, Lord Howe Island Biodiversity Management Plan |author=Anon |year=2007 |series= |publisher= Department of Environment and Climate Change (NSW) |location=Sydney |isbn= 978 1 74122 598 3 |page=228 |url= http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/recovery/lord-howe/pubs/lord-howe-island-appendices.pdf }}</ref><ref name=IUCN>{{cite web| url= http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Zygogynum~howeanum |title= Zygogynum howeanum (F.Muell.) Vink |work=PlantNET:NSW Flora Online |publisher=National Herbarium of NSW: Sydney|first=P.S. |last=Green |accessdate= 2013-03-20|date= }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nOccurring mainly in moist and sheltered parts of the forests of Lord Howe's southern mountains \u2013 [[Mount Gower|Mounts Gower]] and [[Mount Lidgbird|Lidgbird]] \u2013  the species forms a distinctive component of the vegetation from sea level to the peaks. Small numbers also occur elsewhere on the island.  Within its restricted range it is common and locally abundant.<ref name=lhibmp/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q8075863}}\n\n[[Category:Flora of Lord Howe Island]]\n[[Category:Winteraceae]]\n\n\n{{magnoliid-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Glossy leaf tree Lord Howe Island.jpg\n| status = \n| status_system = \n| genus = Zygogynum\n| species = howeanum\n| authority = ([[Ferdinand von Mueller|F.Muell.]]) [[Willem Vink|Vink]]\n}}\n\n'''''Zygogynum howeanum''''', commonly known as '''hotbark''' or '''hot bark''', is a species of [[plant]] in the [[Winteraceae]] family.  It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Australia]]\u2019s [[subtropical]] [[Lord Howe Island]] in the [[Tasman Sea]].  The specific [[epithet]] refers to the locality.\n\n==Description==\nHotbark is a tree that grows to 13&nbsp;m in height.  It has a dark, smooth trunk. Its large, bluntly pointed leaves are dark green on the upper surface and paler beneath.  The white flowers are 20&nbsp;mm in diameter, flowering from June to December, and are insect-pollinated.  The fruit is a round black berry, 8&nbsp;mm across, containing 5\u201315 small seeds.<ref name=lhibmp>{{cite book |title=Appendices, Lord Howe Island Biodiversity Management Plan |author=Anon |year=2007 |series= |publisher= Department of Environment and Climate Change (NSW) |location=Sydney |isbn= 978 1 74122 598 3 |page=228 |url= http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/threatened/publications/recovery/lord-howe/pubs/lord-howe-island-appendices.pdf }}</ref><ref name=IUCN>{{cite web| url= http://plantnet.rbgsyd.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/NSWfl.pl?page=nswfl&lvl=sp&name=Zygogynum~howeanum |title= Zygogynum howeanum (F.Muell.) Vink |work=PlantNET:NSW Flora Online |publisher=National Herbarium of NSW: Sydney|first=P.S. |last=Green |accessdate= 2013-03-20|date= }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nOccurring mainly in moist and sheltered parts of the forests of Lord Howe's southern mountains \u2013 [[Mount Gower|Mounts Gower]] and [[Mount Lidgbird|Lidgbird]] \u2013  the species forms a distinctive component of the vegetation from sea level to the peaks. Small numbers also occur elsewhere on the island.  Within its restricted range it is common and locally abundant.<ref name=lhibmp/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q8075863}}\n\n[[Category:Flora of Lord Howe Island]]\n[[Category:Winteraceae]]\n\n\n{{magnoliid-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zygogynum_howeanum"}
{"title_page": "Baru Bian", "text_new": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Tuan]]\n| name = Baru Bian\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| image        = \n| image_size   = \n| office = [[Minister of Works (Malaysia)|Minister of Works]]\n[[File:BaruBian2.jpg|thumb|Key Note Address by YB Baru Bian]]\n| monarch = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister =[[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| constituency     = [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]]\n| term_start       = 2 July 2018\n| term_end         = 24 February 2020\n| deputy           = [[Mohd Anuar Mohd Tahir]]\n| \n|  \n| predecessor      = [[Fadillah Yusof]]\n| successor        = [[Fadillah Yusof]]\n| office2 = Chairman of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (Sarawak)\n| term_start2 = 2009\n| term_end2 = 2020\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 =\n| constituency_MP3 = [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]], [[Sarawak]]\n| parliament3 = Malaysian\n| majority3 = 486 ([[Malaysian general election, 2018|2018]])\n| term_start3 = 10 May 2018\n| term_end3 =\n| predecessor3 = [[Joseph Entulu Belaun]]\n| successor3 =\n| office4 =\n| term_start4 = 16 April 2011\n| term_end4 =\n| predecessor4 = Nelson Balang Rining\n| successor4 =\n| majority4 = 473 ([[Sarawak state election, 2011|2011]]) <br /> 538 ([[Sarawak state election, 2016|2016]])\n| assembly4 = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM4 = [[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|09|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lawas]], [[Crown Colony of Sarawak]] {{small|(now [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]]}}\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = {{MAS}}\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak|Sarawak Native People's Party]] (PBDS) {{small|(1987-2004)}}<br/> [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) {{small|(2008-2020)}}<br/> [[Independent politician|Independent]]<ref>[https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/11/baru-bian-clarifies-he-has-not-joined-bersatu-is-an-independent-mp/1845483 I am not joining BERSATU]</ref> {{small|(2020-now)}}\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] {{small|(2008-2015)}}<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) {{small|(2015-2020)}}<br /> [[Perikatan Nasional]] (PN)\n| alma_mater = [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]]<br />[[University of Melbourne]]\n| spouse = Yu Ching Sieu\n| children =\n| occupation = Politician<br />Lawyer\n| relations =\n| website = {{URL|http://www.barubian.net/}}\n| footnotes =\n|}}\n\n\n'''Baru Bian''' (born 9 September 1958) is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] [[politician]]. He is the member of parliament of [[Selangau]] winning in 2018 Malaysia General Election. He is formerly the Sarawak Chief of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party (PKR)]] in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] governing coalition formerly serving as the [[Minister of Works (Malaysia)|Minister of Works]] of [[Malaysia]]. He created history when he became the first leader of the [[Lun Bawang]] community to be appointed as a [[cabinet minister]].<ref name=\"history\">{{cite news |title=Baru Bian creates history |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/03/baru-bian-creates-history/ |accessdate=20 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=3 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704025517/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/03/baru-bian-creates-history/ |archivedate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:BaruBian5.jpg|thumb|Attending Community Event]]\n\n\n==Early life and career==\nBaru Bian was born in an impoverished [[Lun Bawang]] family on 9 September 1958,<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> to Bian Labo (father) and Takong Taie (mother) in [[Long Lopeng]], [[Sarawak]].<ref name=\"Awakening\">{{cite book |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |last2=Deborah |first2=Loh |title=The Long Awakening |date=2014 |publisher=Baru Bian |location=Kuching, Sarawak |isbn=978-967-12316-0-9 |language=English}}</ref><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages iii, and i.v</ref> The ancestry of Baru Bian can be traced back to Berunut area, near the Adang river, where the latter is the tributary of the [[Limbang River]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 38</ref> All the genuine Lun Bawang people should be able to trace their ancestry to one single common ancestor named Terur Aco. Baru Bian and his siblings are the twentieth generation since the first Lun Bawang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 40</ref>  He is the third child and the eldest son in the family. He has six siblings. His elder sisters are Mina and Serina. Freddie is his younger brother, followed by a sister named Sigang, a brother Paulus, and another sister named Litad.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Both Baru's parents were pastors.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> Baru's father, Bian Labo was trained at [[Lawas]] bible school which was under the [[Sidang Injil Borneo]] (SIB) church.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Baru's family moved from one village to another because his father was posted to different villages every year.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Brought up in a Christian family since childhood, Baru was taught of discipline and doing the right things by his father.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> \n\n\nBaru met his current wife Ching Sieu during his studies at Melbourne, Australia when he joined Overseas Christian Fellowship (OCF).<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 31</ref> Baru returned to Malaysia after graduation in 1986, Ching Sieu was still studying for another year for her double degree. She only returned to Malaysia in 1987. Baru and Ching Sieu was married on 17 December 1988.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 146</ref> Baru and Ching Sieu raised three children, all three are now practicing Lawyers.<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> Meanwhile, Ching Sieu is a full-time housewife.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 223</ref>\n\nBaru's father died of stomach cancer in 1993 at the age of 62 and was buried at Miri.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 38</ref>\n\n===Education===\nBy the age of seven or eight, he followed his father into the jungle to learn hunting and fishing. As he became older, he would learn jungle survival skills, geography and boundary of the ancestral lands, and memorise twenty generations of ancestral names.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 14</ref> He attended Primary 1 to 2 at Long Lellang (1966 to 1967), Primary 3 to 4 at Long Semado (1968-1969), and passed common entrance examination at Long Napir (1970 to 1971).<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\">{{cite web |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |title=Curriculum vitae |url=http://www.barubian.net/p/curriculum-vitae.html |publisher=barubian.net |accessdate=1 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218132510/http://www.barubian.net/p/curriculum-vitae.html |archivedate=18 February 2018}}</ref> After that, he attended Limbang secondary school until Form 5.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 12</ref> At one point, he would need to wear modified school blouse left by her sister for the secondary school.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 13</ref> He need to hike in the jungles for three days before reaching [[Lawas]] and another day journey to reach [[Limbang]].<ref name=\"Fighter\">{{cite news |last1=Sharon |first1=Ling |title=A fighter with big dreams |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/29/a-fighter-with-big-dreams-from-the-courts-to-the-august-house-this-native-land-rights-lawyer-turned/ |accessdate=20 November 2018 |publisher=The Star (Malaysia) |date=29 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729030515/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/29/a-fighter-with-big-dreams-from-the-courts-to-the-august-house-this-native-land-rights-lawyer-turned/ |archivedate=29 July 2018}}</ref> His experiences during journeys through the jungles and mountain streams led him to understand the value of [[Aboriginal title#Malaysia|Native Customary Rights]] (NCR) for ''pemakai menoa'' (territorial domain) and ''pulau galau'' (communal forest reserve) and also the environmental protection.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> During the year-end school holidays in 1980, Baru Bian interviewed his father and his uncle Lasong Labo about the history of their family's NCR land. He drew the boundaries of their NCR land and signed by the village headman. The map later proved to be useful in fighting against six logging companies encroaching their lands in Berunut from 1986 to 1990s.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 15, 105-116</ref>\n\nHe attended Kolej Tun Datu Tuanku Haji Bujang for Form 6 at Tanjong Lobang, [[Miri]], Sarawak. He got a satisfactory result in [[GCE Ordinary Level]] examination.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 12, 24</ref> After completing his secondary education, he served as a temporary teacher at SMK Medamit, [[Limbang]] from 1979 to 1981. He taught Geography, History, Physical Education and General Science there.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 25</ref><ref name=\"history\"/> His passion towards native land rights had led him pursued his tertiary education at Institut Teknology Mara (ITM) (now [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]] (UiTM)), [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]] in Diploma in Law (DIL).<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> His uncle, Libat Langub, who was a former student at ITM, encouraged him to study law there.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 25</ref> He went to Melbourne to further his studies on Law in 1985.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 31</ref> He applied for scholarship from ITM but was denied. Therefore, he decided to take a study loan instead.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 28</ref> He subsequently obtained [[Bachelor of Laws|Bachelor of Laws (LL.B)]] from the [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]] in 1986.<ref name=\"history\"/> After his graduation in Australia, Baru decided to come back to Malaysia to serve the needy instead of applying for permanent residency in Australia.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 145</ref>\n\n===Law career===\nUpon graduation, he became a trainee in a law firm named Rashid & Lee in [[Kuala Lumpur]] for six months before the law firm stopped paying allowances due to financial difficulties. He then continued his training at Eddy Chung & Co and was employed there until he returned to Kuching in 1988.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 146</ref> Baru was subsequently admitted to the [[Malaysian Bar|Malayan Bar]] as a lawyer and [[solicitor]].<ref name=\"history\"/> By 1990, Baru became a partner in the firm of Messrs Anthony Ting, Baru Bian & Co. in Kuching, Sarawak.<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> Baru taught himself about native customary rights law through Sahabat Alam Malaysia (SAM), an NGO led by [[Harrison Ngau Laing]], an environmentalist. Baru would later became a legal advisor for SAM.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 147</ref> In the same year, he represented SAM to [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]] to protest against the [[International Tropical Timber Organization]] (ITTO) for not including the issues of native customary rights in their report. It was also at this time that Baru Bian met the Swiss activist, [[Bruno Manser]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 147</ref> Bruno would later helped Baru to raise RM 30,000 from overseas supporters to fund Baru's [[1991 Sarawak state election|1991 election]] endeavour.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 148</ref> However, Malaysian embassy officials would later took a photo of Baru Bian and Bruno Manser in Yokohama and used the photo to depict Baru as a traitor to Malaysian interests in 1991 election.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 151</ref>\n\nBaru filed his first NCR case in 1991 on behalf of his extended family whose ancestral lands in Berunut was encroached by logging companies. However, the case was pending in court after two years. Therefore, Baru and his family members took part in timber blockades which successfully led Samling (a logging company) to compensate them RM 100,000. As part of the agreement, Baru withdrew the court case.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 105-116</ref><ref name=\"Fighter\"/> He set up Messrs Baru Bian Advocates and Solicitors in [[Kuching]] in 1992.<ref name=\"history\"/> Baru would later found a legal partner named See Chee How. See is a human rights activist and a lawyer from Kuching. Together, they were involved in numerous native land rights cases.<ref name=\"Money Logging\"/> Baru also took up cases related to wrongful arrests or jailed without [[Remand (detention)|remand]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 119-120</ref> In 2001, Baru Bian won the Rumah Nor Nyawai case in Sarawak High Court. This was the first time in the history of Malaysian courts that NCR rights was upheld.<ref name=\"Money Logging\">{{cite book |last1=Lukas |first1=Straumann |title=Money Logging On the Trail of the Asian Timber Mafia |date=2014 |publisher=[[Bergli Books]] |location=Basel, Switzerland |isbn=978-3-905252-72-9 |pages=205 |edition=First |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-F8aCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT205&lpg=PT205&dq=Rumah+Nor+case+Baru+Bian&source=bl&ots=4zYK2xKiqv&sig=Qr2nH7ho0bjG07J476ClvMBtxow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi7puTQw_DeAhUKKo8KHeyJC9EQ6AEwC3oECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Rumah%20Nor%20case%20Baru%20Bian&f=false |accessdate=2 November 2018 |language=English |chapter= Chapter 6 -  Bruno Manser's legacy}}</ref> In 2007, the [[Federal Court of Malaysia]] upheld the decision on Rumah Nor Nyawai case that ''pemakai menua'' and ''pulau galau'', in addition to ''temuda'' (cultivated land before 1 January 1958) are included in the definition of NCR land.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 128</ref> In March 2011, Baru successfully led to the acquittal of Numpang Suntai who was accused of burning ten items of machinery in a logging camp at Sebangan, [[Simunjan District]] for encroaching the latter's ancestral land.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 120</ref> By 2013, Baru Bian's law firm had processed more than 200 native land rights cases in court.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 131</ref>\n\nBaru Bian's belief in the freedom of religion guaranteed by the [[Constitution of Malaysia]] had prompted him to take up cases for those who wished to leave the religion of Islam.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |title=Baru Bian: Court of Appeal Decision a Letdown for converts out of Islam |url=https://www.borneotoday.net/baru-bian-court-of-appeal-decision-a-letdown-for-converts-out-of-islam/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |agency=Press statement |publisher=Borneo Today |date=12 November 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117020750/https://www.borneotoday.net/baru-bian-court-of-appeal-decision-a-letdown-for-converts-out-of-islam/ |archivedate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wanita Melayu Diwakili Peguam Baru Bian Gagal Dalam Rayuan Kes Murtad (A Malay lady who was represented by lawyer Baru Bian lost the appeal in an apostasy case) |url=https://www.menara.my/wanita-melayu-diwakili-peguam-baru-bian-gagal-dalam-rayuan-kes-murtad/ |publisher=menara.my |accessdate=23 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223124445/https://www.menara.my/wanita-melayu-diwakili-peguam-baru-bian-gagal-dalam-rayuan-kes-murtad/ |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Law is silent on Muslim converts wishing to leave Islam \u2013 Baru |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=11 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330175031/http://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/ |archivedate=30 March 2018}}</ref> His representations in the [[apostasy]] cases has drawn criticisms from [[Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS), accusing him of contempt against the Islamic religion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru Bian blasts death threats, insults over apostasy case |url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/02/28/baru-bian-blasts-death-threats-insults-over-apostasy-case/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Free Malaysia Today |date=28 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Baru Bian hina umat Islam Sarawak' (Baru Bian insulted Islam in Sarawak) |url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/413661 |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Malaysiakini |date=27 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223132425/https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/413661 |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kamarul |first1=Zaman Yusoff |title=Baru Bian juara Kristianisasi Sarawak (Baru Bian is the champion of christianisation in Sarawak) |url=http://www.harakahdaily.net/index.php/berita/15-tanah-air/5501-baru-bian-juara-kristianisasi-sarawak |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Harakah Daily |date=28 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403152628/http://www.harakahdaily.net/index.php/berita/15-tanah-air/5501-baru-bian-juara-kristianisasi-sarawak |archivedate=3 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1987, Baru joined [[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak]] (PBDS) because the party was advocating NCR rights in Sarawak.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 1989, Baru was elected as PBDS Youth Executive Council member.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 171</ref> Baru was also a supreme council member of PBDS.<ref name=\"history\"/> He first contested against Sarawak [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) governing coalition at [[Lawas (state constituency)|Lawas]] in 1991 but lost. After that, PBDS started negotiating to rejoin Sarawak BN in 1992 and was subsequently admitted into BN in 1994.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oorjitham|first1=Santha|title=Dayak welfare was his priority|url=http://www2.nst.com.my/nation/general/dayak-welfare-was-his-priority-1.355519|accessdate=17 May 2015|publisher=New Straits Times|date=14 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920085822/http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/dayak-welfare-was-his-priority-1.355519|archivedate=20 September 2013 }}</ref> One of the condition for PBDS to rejoin BN was to stop raising the NCR issues within the state government. However, Baru Bian decided to continue his pursue towards NCR rights cases in court.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 2004, Baru decided to quit PBDS and went to contest against BN in [[2004 Ba'kelalan by-election|Ba'kelalan by-election]] as an independent but lost again. Baru believed in continuing to uphold the NCR lands among the natives and the need to change the Sarawak state government in order to solve the NCR problems permanently.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> Baru later joined [[Malaysian Dayak Congress]] (MDS). However, MDS did not get registered before [[2006 Sarawak state election]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 184</ref> Therefore, Baru contested again for [[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]] under [[Sarawak National Party]] (SNAP) ticket and lost for the third time. He filed an election petition to [[Miri, Malaysia|Miri]] High Court on BN's vote buying activities in Ba'kelalan. However, the petition was struck out on technicality grounds.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 192-193</ref> He then decided to retire from politics because he already lost three times in elections.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/>\n\nHowever, when BN lost its two-thirds majority in the parliament and five states to the opposition during the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], Baru decided to join politics again to strengthen the two-party system. He joined [[Parti Keadilan Rakyat]] (PKR) in the same year.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 2009, Baru was appointed as the chairman of PKR Sarawak.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> He then proceed to win the Ba'kelalan state constituency during [[2011 Sarawak state election]], having defeated the candidate for the BN coalition, Willie Liau, who is also his nephew, by a narrow 473-vote majority.<ref>{{cite news |title=I\u2019m still a winnable candidate in Ba\u2019 Kelalan \u2014 Balang |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/07/22/im-still-a-winnable-candidate-in-ba-kelalan-balang/ |accessdate=1 December 2018 |date=22 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714172227/http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/07/22/im-still-a-winnable-candidate-in-ba-kelalan-balang/ |archivedate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=William |first1=Mangor |title=Baru Bian: Sarawakians want to see changes |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2015/07/23/baru-bian-sarawakians-want-to-see-changes/ |accessdate=1 December 2018 |publisher=Free Malaysia Today |date=23 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065656/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2015/07/23/baru-bian-sarawakians-want-to-see-changes/ |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Sarawak chief minister [[Adenan Satem]] invited Baru Bian to join BN, however, Baru declined the offer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Philip |first1=Kiew |title=\u2018Join BN, Baru Bian\u2019 |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/05/31/join-bn-baru-bian/ |accessdate=26 January 2019 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618235255/http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/05/31/join-bn-baru-bian/ |archivedate=18 June 2018}}</ref> Baru retained the seat in the [[2016 Sarawak state election]] with an increased majority of 538 votes, also against Willie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sarawak Polls: Baru Bian retains Ba'kelalan seat |url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/05/144278/sarawak-polls-baru-bian-retains-bakelalan-seat |accessdate=26 November 2018 |agency=New Straits Times |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508124142/https://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/05/144278/sarawak-polls-baru-bian-retains-bakelalan-seat |archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2013 Malaysian general election]], Baru Bian decided to contest in [[Limbang (federal constituency)|Limbang]] parliamentary seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru confirms standing in Limbang |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/03/09/baru-confirms-standing-in-limbang/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=9 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223223450/http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/03/09/baru-confirms-standing-in-limbang/ |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref> However, he was defeated by a huge margin against BN.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru admits stunned by a huge margin |url=https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-borneo-post/20130507/281930245490336 |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=7 March 2013}}</ref>\nDuring the [[2018 Malaysian general election]], NCR issues at [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]] prompt Baru to contest for the seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=NCR issues prompted me to stand in Selangau \u2013 Baru |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/04/29/ncr-issues-prompted-me-to-stand-in-selangau-baru/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=29 April 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430002606/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/04/29/ncr-issues-prompted-me-to-stand-in-selangau-baru/ |archivedate=30 April 2018}}</ref> He subsequently won the parliamentary seat against BN's Rita Sarimah with a majority of 486 votes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jane |first1=Moh |title=Baru Bian secures maiden parliament win in Selangau |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/05/10/baru-bian-secures-maiden-parliament-win-in-selangau/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=10 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510000120/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/05/10/baru-bian-secures-maiden-parliament-win-in-selangau/ |archivedate=10 May 2018}}</ref> On 2 July 2018, Baru was sworn-in as the Minister of Works of Malaysia at [[Istana Negara, Jalan Tuanku Abdul Halim|National Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrew |first1=Sia |title=Baru Bian, the first Lun Bawang minister, fought hard for Sarawak natives' land rights |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/baru-bian-first-lun-bawang-minister/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Star (Malaysia) |date=2 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703133337/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/baru-bian-first-lun-bawang-minister/ |archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New members of Malaysia's Cabinet sworn in |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/new-memebrs-of-malaysias-cabinet-sworn-in |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911082355/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/new-memebrs-of-malaysias-cabinet-sworn-in |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, he and 10 others Member of Parliament lead by [[Mohamed Azmin Ali]] decided to leave [[People's Justice Party, Malaysia|PKR]] and decided to support [[BERSATU]] Prime Minister candidate [[Mahathir Mohamad]] to remain as the Prime Minister. However [[Mahathir Mohamad]] refuse returning as the Prime Minister of Malaysia so [[BERSATU]] nominated [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] as the nominee for the Prime Minister position. After [[PH]] change their support from [[Anwar Ibrahim]] to [[Mahathir Mohamad]] as the Prime Minister, he (Baru Bian) and Jonathan Yasin who are the 11 MP's who's leaving [[People's Justice Party, Malaysia|PKR]] came back supporting [[Mahathir Mohamad]] as the Prime Minister rather than [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]. [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] make a disgusting move by giving an executive position to Jonathan Yasin in his new back-door government. It is said that he (Baru Bian) and 10 others ex-PKR MP's are officially a member of [[BERSATU]].\n\n==Hobbies and interests==\nBaru learned ''Ngajat'' dance during his primary school years at Long Lellang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 11</ref> Baru is able to sing songs in [[alto]] since he was in Form 4.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 3</ref> Baru started to play football while he was in Form 6.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 24</ref>\n\n[[File:BaruBian4.jpg|thumb|Encouraging Youth]]\n\n==Religion==\nBaru was baptised at [[Limbang River]] in 1973 by a New Zealand missionary named Murray Munroe.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> A few months before baptism, a testimony given by a former gangster from Singapore during an Inter-School Christian Fellowship (ISCF) meeting had strengthen Baru's belief in Christianity.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> Baru started to play guitar for Christian songs while he was a member of ISCF at SMK Limbang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> He later become the president of ICSF during Form 4 and Form 5. He participated in Young Christian Students Movement (YCSM) year-end mission trips during his secondary school years.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 20-22</ref> During his years at ITM, he attended Full Gospel Assembly Church service at Old Klang Road.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 29</ref> He also attended a Christian Fellowship in ITM.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 28</ref> When Baru studied at Melbourne, Australia, he attended Overseas Christian Fellowship (OCF).<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 31</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|[[1991 Sarawak state election|1991]]\n|'''[[Lawas (state constituency)|Lawas]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak|PBDS]])\n|align=\"right\" |2,433\n|28.59%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Tengah Ali Hassin''' ([[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|'''PBB''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''6,076'''\n|'''71.41%'''\n|8,619\n|3,643\n|74.10%\n|-\n|[[2004 Ba'kelalan by-election|2004]]\n|rowspan=4|'''[[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,391\n|32.85%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Nelson Balang Rining''' ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|'''SPDP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,843'''\n|'''67.15%'''\n|4,313\n|1,452\n|56.04%\n|-\n|[[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]]\n|{td bgcolor=\"#717190\"}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Sarawak National Party|SNAP]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,589\n|43.50%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Nelson Balang Rining''' ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|'''SPDP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,064'''\n|'''56.50%'''\n|3,680\n|475\n|58.56%\n|-\n|[[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]]\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Baru Bian'''}} ([[