donwong", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scottie_Pippen"}
{"title_page": "Donald Trump (song)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{for|the Time song|Pandemonium (The Time album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Donald Trump\n| cover      = Donald-trump-by-mac-miller.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mac Miller]]\n| album      = [[Best Day Ever (mixtape)|Best Day Ever]]\n| released   = February 9, 2011\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2010\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 2:45\n| label      = [[Rostrum Records|Rostrum]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Mac Miller|Malcolm McCormick]]\n* [[Sap (producer)|Jonathan King]]\n}}\n| producer   = [[Sap (producer)|Sap]]\n| chronology = [[Mac Miller]]\n| prev_title = On and On\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Frick Park Market]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|74TFS8r_SMI|\"Donald Trump\"}} }}\n}}\n\n\"'''Donald Trump'''\" is a song by American rapper [[Mac Miller]], released as the only single from his [[mixtape]] ''[[Best Day Ever (mixtape)|Best Day Ever]]'' (2011). The melody, which is played throughout the song, is [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] from \"Vesuvius\" by [[Sufjan Stevens]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Zisook|first=Brian|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2017-06-15-mac-miller-donald-trump-free|title=Mac Miller Cleared Sufjan Stevens Sample on \"Donald Trump\" For Free|date=June 15, 2017|accessdate=August 4, 2019|website=DJ Booth}}</ref> The song's [[music video]] was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on March 3, 2011, while the single was released digitally on May 17, 2011.\n\nThe money-inspired song references [[Donald Trump]], who, five years after the song's release, was [[2016 United States presidential election|elected]] as the [[List of Presidents of the United States|45th]] [[president of the United States]]. Trump and Miller feuded over the song for years, with Trump demanding [[royalties]] for the use of his name.\n\n<nowiki>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------</nowiki>\n\nDonald Trump has many problems that he needs to get checked, here are some of them- <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/thesaurus|title=Thesaurus by Merriam-Webster|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n# Orange Skin Color\n# His love of wearing red ties\n# Big Body Shape\n# His deep annoying devil-like voice\n# He owns a pet Whale\n# He adopts children for child labor\n# WHOEVER DELETES THIS EDIT AND CALL IT VANDAL IS LIVING WITH THERE MUMMY AND STILL DRINK FROM MUMMY'S BOOBS\n# Mac Miller is an idiot\n# I can't think of anymore\n# Sorry \n\n'''[[User:Kayau/Bite you]]'''\n\n==Background==\nAfter performing the song for several weeks, [[Mac Miller]] released \"Donald Trump\" as a free download on February 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Big Homie|url=http://rapradar.com/2011/02/09/new-music-mac-miller-donald-trump/|title=New Music: Mac Miller \"Donald Trump\"|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=August 4, 2019|website=Rap Radar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lilah|first=Rose|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/mac-miller-donald-trump-song.187854.html|title=Mac Miller \u2013 Donald Trump|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=August 4, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop}}</ref> Its [[music video]], directed by Ian Wolfson, was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on March 3, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74TFS8r_SMI|title=Mac Miller \u2013 Donald Trump|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306001451/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74TFS8r_SMI|archivedate=March 6, 2011|url-status=live|date=March 3, 2011|accessdate=December 6, 2019|publisher=Rostrum Records|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TreeJTV/videos|title=Mac Miller|via=YouTube|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> The song was included in Miller's 2011 [[mixtape]] ''[[Best Day Ever (mixtape)|Best Day Ever]]'', and commercially released by [[Rostrum Records]] as a single on May 17, 2011.<ref name=\"iTunes single\" />\n\nThe money-inspired song refers to [[Donald Trump]], particularly Miller's ambitions to become wealthy and successful like him (\"Take over the world when I'm on my Donald Trump shit / Look at all this money, ain't that some shit?\").<ref name=\"Complex iTunes election\">{{cite web|last=Espionza|first=Joshua|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2016/11/mac-miller-2011-donald-trump-song-returns-to-top-30-itunes|title=Mac Miller's 2011 Hit \"Donald Trump\" Surges on iTunes|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=November 9, 2016|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> According to Miller, the use of Trump's name was a last-minute decision,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/xxl-magazine/2011/07/donald-trump-gives-mac-miller-props-for-donald-song-via-twitter/|title=Mac Miller talks Twitter exchange with Donald Trump|date=July 14, 2011|accessdate=December 6, 2019|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]}}</ref> and that he \"was just somebody who symbolized financial success to everybody at that time\".<ref name=\"VF January 2016\" /> When the music video surpassed 20 million views in August 2011, Trump released a YouTube video congratulating Miller, and branded him \"the new [[Eminem]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Horowitz |first=Steven J. |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16501/title.donald-trump-brands-mac-miller-the-next-eminem |title=Donald Trump Brands Mac Miller \"The Next Eminem\"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209055544/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16501/title.donald-trump-brands-mac-miller-the-next-eminem|archivedate=February 9, 2012|url-status=dead|website=HipHopDX |date=August 18, 2011 |accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Zaru, 2015\">{{cite news|last1=Zaru|first1=Deena|title=What hip-hop lyrics tell us about Donald Trump|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/02/politics/donald-trump-rich-hip-hop-lyrics-rap/|accessdate=November 26, 2016|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=September 2, 2015}}</ref> Miller responded appreciatively, but played down any comparisons between himself and Eminem.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chandler|first=D. L.|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2495948/mac-miller-responds-to-donald-trumps-eminem-comparison/|title=Mac Miller Responds To Donald Trump\u2019s Eminem Comparison |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the song garnered more streams in 2012, Trump took a more aggressive tone and demanded [[royalties]] for using his name, igniting a feud with Miller.<ref name=\"VF January 2016\">{{cite news |last1=Makarechi |first1=Kia |title=Mac Miller, Donald Trump's Least Favorite Rapper, Revisits Feud |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/01/mac-miller-donald-trump-feud |accessdate=June 13, 2016 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=January 25, 2016}}</ref> In a January 2013 interview, Miller insulted Trump and said he was bothered by Trump taking credit for the song's success. He added that he could have referenced [[Bill Gates]] instead and that the name did not matter. In response, Trump threatened Miller with a lawsuit via a series of [[Twitter|tweets]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Nostro|first=Lauren|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/01/donald-trump-threatens-to-sue-mac-miller|title=Donald Trump Threatens Mac Miller With Lawsuit, Calls Him an \"Ungrateful Dog\"|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=August 4, 2019|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> In July 2015, Trump changed his attitude toward Miller again when he ended an interview by praising Miller's song as it approached 100 million views.<ref name=\"Cirilli, 2015\">{{cite news |last1=Cirilli |first1=Kevin |title=Trump praises rapper's 'great' song about him |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/in-the-know/in-the-know/248911-trump-praises-rappers-great-song-about-him|accessdate=November 26, 2016 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=July 23, 2015}}</ref> During [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]], Miller denounced Trump and urged people to not elect him.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zaru|first=Deena|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/12/17/politics/mac-miller-donald-trump-feud/index.html|title=Mac Miller resurrects Donald Trump feud|date=December 17, 2015|accessdate=August 4, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Miller said on ''[[The Nightly Show with Larry Wilmore]]'' that he \"hated\" Trump, and described him as \"an egomaniacal, attention-thirsty, psychopathic, power-hungry, delusional waste of skin and bones\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Joe|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7014823/mac-miller-donald-trump-racist-nightly-show|title=Mac Miller to Donald Trump: 'Make America Great Again? You Want to Make America White Again'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314003725/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7014823/mac-miller-donald-trump-racist-nightly-show|archivedate=March 14, 2016|url-status=live|date=March 10, 2016|accessdate=August 4, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zaru|first1=Deena|title=Mac Miller: Donald Trump wants to 'make America white again'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/03/11/politics/mac-miller-donald-trump/|accessdate=August 4, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Stub section|date=December 2018}}\n''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s Nick Catucci called the track an \"irresistible bro-down\".<ref name=RS>{{cite web|author=Nick Catucci |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/watching-movies-with-the-sound-off-20130618 |title=Mac Miller, 'Watching Movies With the Sound Off &#124; Album Reviews |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=June 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Donald Trump\" was Miller's first song to chart on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], entering at number 80 on chart dated June 11, 2011,<ref name=\"First charts\">{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8474360/mac-miller-music-streams-increased-970-percent-death|title=Mac Miller's Music Streams Increased 970% Following Death|date=September 10, 2018|accessdate=February 13, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215120015/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8474360/mac-miller-music-streams-increased-970-percent-death|archive-date=February 15, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and peaked at number 75 on January 7, 2012.<ref name=\"BB Hot 100\" /> On March 19, 2013, it was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] for digital download sales in excess of one million.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/riaa-announces-ten-first-time-digital-award-recipients/|title=RIAA Announces Ten First-Time Digital Award Recipients|date=April 18, 2013|accessdate=August 4, 2019|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America}}</ref>\n\nThe song also charted in [[SNEP]], the official French Singles Chart, peaking at number 110 in June 2012.<ref name=\"SNEP\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=\"iTunes single\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/donald-trump-single/id438785802 |title=Donald Trump \u2013 Single by Mac Miller |publisher=[[Rostrum Records]]|via=[[iTunes Store]]|date=May 17, 2011 |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n| title1 = Donald Trump\n| note1 = explicit\n| length1 = 2:45\n\n| title2 = Donald Trump\n| note2 = clean\n| length2 = 2:45\n}}\n\n== Charts ==\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011\u201318)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|110|artist=Mac Miller|song=Donald Trump|accessdate=August 3, 2019|refname=SNEP}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddigitalsongs|47|artist=Mac Miller|song=Donald Trump|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|75|artist=Mac Miller|song=Donald Trump|accessdate=August 3, 2019|refname=BB Hot 100}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Denmark|award=Gold|type=single|relyear=2011|title=Donald Trump|artist=Mac Miller|certyear=2013|id=6340|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|award=Platinum|type=single|relyear=2011|accessdate=November 19, 2012|title=Donald Trump|artist=Mac Miller|certyear=2012|digital=true|refname=RIAA}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Donald Trump in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genius.com/Mac-miller-donald-trump-lyrics Lyrics of \"Donald Trump\" by Mac Miller at Genius]\n\n{{Mac Miller}}\n{{Trump media}}\n\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n[[Category:2011 debut singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Mac Miller songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Sap (producer)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mac Miller]]\n[[Category:Sufjan Stevens]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{for|the Time song|Pandemonium (The Time album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Donald Trump\n| cover      = Donald-trump-by-mac-miller.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mac Miller]]\n| album      = [[Best Day Ever (mixtape)|Best Day Ever]]\n| released   = February 9, 2011\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2010\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 2:45\n| label      = [[Rostrum Records|Rostrum]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Mac Miller|Malcolm McCormick]]\n* [[Sap (producer)|Jonathan King]]\n}}\n| producer   = [[Sap (producer)|Sap]]\n| chronology = [[Mac Miller]]\n| prev_title = On and On\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Frick Park Market]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|74TFS8r_SMI|\"Donald Trump\"}} }}\n}}\n\n\"'''Donald Trump'''\" is a song by American rapper [[Mac Miller]], released as the only single from his [[mixtape]] ''[[Best Day Ever (mixtape)|Best Day Ever]]'' (2011). The melody, which is played throughout the song, is [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] from \"Vesuvius\" by [[Sufjan Stevens]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Zisook|first=Brian|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2017-06-15-mac-miller-donald-trump-free|title=Mac Miller Cleared Sufjan Stevens Sample on \"Donald Trump\" For Free|date=June 15, 2017|accessdate=August 4, 2019|website=DJ Booth}}</ref> The song's [[music video]] was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on March 3, 2011, while the single was released digitally on May 17, 2011.\n\nThe money-inspired song references [[Donald Trump]], who, five years after the song's release, was [[2016 United States presidential election|elected]] as the [[List of Presidents of the United States|45th]] [[president of the United States]]. Trump and Miller feuded over the song for years, with Trump demanding [[royalties]] for the use of his name.\n\n==Background==\nAfter performing the song for several weeks, [[Mac Miller]] released \"Donald Trump\" as a free download on February 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Big Homie|url=http://rapradar.com/2011/02/09/new-music-mac-miller-donald-trump/|title=New Music: Mac Miller \"Donald Trump\"|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=August 4, 2019|website=Rap Radar}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lilah|first=Rose|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/mac-miller-donald-trump-song.187854.html|title=Mac Miller \u2013 Donald Trump|date=February 9, 2011|accessdate=August 4, 2019|website=HotNewHipHop}}</ref> Its [[music video]], directed by Ian Wolfson, was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on March 3, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74TFS8r_SMI|title=Mac Miller \u2013 Donald Trump|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306001451/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=74TFS8r_SMI|archivedate=March 6, 2011|url-status=live|date=March 3, 2011|accessdate=December 6, 2019|publisher=Rostrum Records|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TreeJTV/videos|title=Mac Miller|via=YouTube|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> The song was included in Miller's 2011 [[mixtape]] ''[[Best Day Ever (mixtape)|Best Day Ever]]'', and commercially released by [[Rostrum Records]] as a single on May 17, 2011.<ref name=\"iTunes single\" />\n\nThe money-inspired song refers to [[Donald Trump]], particularly Miller's ambitions to become wealthy and successful like him (\"Take over the world when I'm on my Donald Trump shit / Look at all this money, ain't that some shit?\").<ref name=\"Complex iTunes election\">{{cite web|last=Espionza|first=Joshua|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2016/11/mac-miller-2011-donald-trump-song-returns-to-top-30-itunes|title=Mac Miller's 2011 Hit \"Donald Trump\" Surges on iTunes|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=November 9, 2016|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> According to Miller, the use of Trump's name was a last-minute decision,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/xxl-magazine/2011/07/donald-trump-gives-mac-miller-props-for-donald-song-via-twitter/|title=Mac Miller talks Twitter exchange with Donald Trump|date=July 14, 2011|accessdate=December 6, 2019|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]}}</ref> and that he \"was just somebody who symbolized financial success to everybody at that time\".<ref name=\"VF January 2016\" /> When the music video surpassed 20 million views in August 2011, Trump released a YouTube video congratulating Miller, and branded him \"the new [[Eminem]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Horowitz |first=Steven J. |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16501/title.donald-trump-brands-mac-miller-the-next-eminem |title=Donald Trump Brands Mac Miller \"The Next Eminem\"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209055544/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16501/title.donald-trump-brands-mac-miller-the-next-eminem|archivedate=February 9, 2012|url-status=dead|website=HipHopDX |date=August 18, 2011 |accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Zaru, 2015\">{{cite news|last1=Zaru|first1=Deena|title=What hip-hop lyrics tell us about Donald Trump|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/09/02/politics/donald-trump-rich-hip-hop-lyrics-rap/|accessdate=November 26, 2016|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=September 2, 2015}}</ref> Miller responded appreciatively, but played down any comparisons between himself and Eminem.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chandler|first=D. L.|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2495948/mac-miller-responds-to-donald-trumps-eminem-comparison/|title=Mac Miller Responds To Donald Trump\u2019s Eminem Comparison |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the song garnered more streams in 2012, Trump took a more aggressive tone and demanded [[royalties]] for using his name, igniting a feud with Miller.<ref name=\"VF January 2016\">{{cite news |last1=Makarechi |first1=Kia |title=Mac Miller, Donald Trump's Least Favorite Rapper, Revisits Feud |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/01/mac-miller-donald-trump-feud |accessdate=June 13, 2016 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=January 25, 2016}}</ref> In a January 2013 interview, Miller insulted Trump and said he was bothered by Trump taking credit for the song's success. He added that he could have referenced [[Bill Gates]] instead and that the name did not matter. In response, Trump threatened Miller with a lawsuit via a series of [[Twitter|tweets]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Nostro|first=Lauren|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/01/donald-trump-threatens-to-sue-mac-miller|title=Donald Trump Threatens Mac Miller With Lawsuit, Calls Him an \"Ungrateful Dog\"|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=August 4, 2019|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref> In July 2015, Trump changed his attitude toward Miller again when he ended an interview by praising Miller's song as it approached 100 million views.<ref name=\"Cirilli, 2015\">{{cite news |last1=Cirilli |first1=Kevin |title=Trump praises rapper's 'great' song about him |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/in-the-know/in-the-know/248911-trump-praises-rappers-great-song-about-him|accessdate=November 26, 2016 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=July 23, 2015}}</ref> During [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Trump's 2016 presidential campaign]], Miller denounced Trump and urged people to not elect him.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zaru|first=Deena|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/12/17/politics/mac-miller-donald-trump-feud/index.html|title=Mac Miller resurrects Donald Trump feud|date=December 17, 2015|accessdate=August 4, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Miller said on ''[[The Nightly Show with Larry Wilmore]]'' that he \"hated\" Trump, and described him as \"an egomaniacal, attention-thirsty, psychopathic, power-hungry, delusional waste of skin and bones\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Lynch|first=Joe|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7014823/mac-miller-donald-trump-racist-nightly-show|title=Mac Miller to Donald Trump: 'Make America Great Again? You Want to Make America White Again'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314003725/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7014823/mac-miller-donald-trump-racist-nightly-show|archivedate=March 14, 2016|url-status=live|date=March 10, 2016|accessdate=August 4, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zaru|first1=Deena|title=Mac Miller: Donald Trump wants to 'make America white again'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/03/11/politics/mac-miller-donald-trump/|accessdate=August 4, 2019|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Stub section|date=December 2018}}\n''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s Nick Catucci called the track an \"irresistible bro-down\".<ref name=RS>{{cite web|author=Nick Catucci |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/watching-movies-with-the-sound-off-20130618 |title=Mac Miller, 'Watching Movies With the Sound Off &#124; Album Reviews |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=June 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Donald Trump\" was Miller's first song to chart on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], entering at number 80 on chart dated June 11, 2011,<ref name=\"First charts\">{{cite web|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8474360/mac-miller-music-streams-increased-970-percent-death|title=Mac Miller's Music Streams Increased 970% Following Death|date=September 10, 2018|accessdate=February 13, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215120015/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8474360/mac-miller-music-streams-increased-970-percent-death|archive-date=February 15, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and peaked at number 75 on January 7, 2012.<ref name=\"BB Hot 100\" /> On March 19, 2013, it was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] for digital download sales in excess of one million.<ref name=\"RIAA\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/riaa-announces-ten-first-time-digital-award-recipients/|title=RIAA Announces Ten First-Time Digital Award Recipients|date=April 18, 2013|accessdate=August 4, 2019|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America}}</ref>\n\nThe song also charted in [[SNEP]], the official French Singles Chart, peaking at number 110 in June 2012.<ref name=\"SNEP\" />\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=\"iTunes single\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/donald-trump-single/id438785802 |title=Donald Trump \u2013 Single by Mac Miller |publisher=[[Rostrum Records]]|via=[[iTunes Store]]|date=May 17, 2011 |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n| title1 = Donald Trump\n| note1 = explicit\n| length1 = 2:45\n\n| title2 = Donald Trump\n| note2 = clean\n| length2 = 2:45\n}}\n\n== Charts ==\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011\u201318)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|110|artist=Mac Miller|song=Donald Trump|accessdate=August 3, 2019|refname=SNEP}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddigitalsongs|47|artist=Mac Miller|song=Donald Trump|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|75|artist=Mac Miller|song=Donald Trump|accessdate=August 3, 2019|refname=BB Hot 100}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Denmark|award=Gold|type=single|relyear=2011|title=Donald Trump|artist=Mac Miller|certyear=2013|id=6340|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|award=Platinum|type=single|relyear=2011|accessdate=November 19, 2012|title=Donald Trump|artist=Mac Miller|certyear=2012|digital=true|refname=RIAA}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Donald Trump in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genius.com/Mac-miller-donald-trump-lyrics Lyrics of \"Donald Trump\" by Mac Miller at Genius]\n\n{{Mac Miller}}\n{{Trump media}}\n\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n[[Category:2011 debut singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Mac Miller songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Sap (producer)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mac Miller]]\n[[Category:Sufjan Stevens]]\n", "name_user": "Ajsoal2", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clarification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Trump_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Zygogynum tanyostigma", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image =\n| image_caption =\n| status = VU\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= |title= '''' |year= 2016|page= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n| genus = Zygogynum\n| species = tanyostigma\n| authority = [[Willem Vink|Vink]]\n}}\n\n'''''Zygogynum tanyostigma''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Winteraceae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[New Caledonia]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Jaffr\u00e9, T. ''et al.'' 1998.  [https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/37417/all ''Zygogynum tanyostigma''].   [https://web.archive.org/web/20140627000000/http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species.]  Downloaded on 24 August 2007.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3576408}}\n\n[[Category:Endemic flora of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Winteraceae]]\n[[Category:Vulnerable plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{magnoliid-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image =\n| image_caption =\n| status = VU\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| genus = Zygogynum\n| species = tanyostigma\n| authority = [[Willem Vink|Vink]]\n}}\n\n'''''Zygogynum tanyostigma''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the [[Winteraceae]] family. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[New Caledonia]].\n\n==References==\n* Jaffr\u00e9, T. ''et al.'' 1998.  [http://www.iucnredlist.org/search/details.php/37417/all ''Zygogynum tanyostigma''].   [https://web.archive.org/web/20140627000000/http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species.]  Downloaded on 24 August 2007.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3576408}}\n\n[[Category:Endemic flora of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Winteraceae]]\n[[Category:Vulnerable plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{magnoliid-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zygogynum_tanyostigma"}
{"title_page": "John Corabi", "text_new": "{{short description|Heavy metal singer and guitarist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{POV|date=March 2013}}\n{{original research|date=March 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2013}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = John Corabi\n|background = solo_singer\n|image = The Dead Daisies - Hamburg Harley Days 2017 18.jpg\n|caption = John Corabi in 2017\n|birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|4|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|origin = \n|genre = [[Hard rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[glam metal]]\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter, singer\n|instrument = Vocals, guitar, bass\n|years_active = 1988\u2013present\n|label = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n|associated_acts = [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], [[The Scream (band)|The Scream]], [[Ratt]], [[Brides of Destruction]], [[Angora (band)|Angora]], [[Eric Singer Project|ESP]], [[Union (band)|Union]], Angel City Outlaws, Twenty 4 Seven, Cardboard Vampyres, [[The Dead Daisies]]\n| website = {{URL|johncorabi.com/}}\n\n|\n}}\n'''John Corabi''' (born April 26, 1959) is an American hard rock singer and guitarist. He was the frontman of [[The Scream (band)|The Scream]] during 1989. He was also the frontman of [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] between 1994 and 1996 during original frontman [[Vince Neil]]'s hiatus from the band.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Scream Bio \u2013 Sleaze Roxx|url=https://sleazeroxx.com/bios/the-scream-bio/}}</ref>\n\nCorabi is considered a \"rock journeyman\"<ref>{{cite web|title=John Corabi &#124; Biography & History &#124; AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-corabi-mn0000218589/biography}}</ref> with a long list of collaborations with established acts such as [[Angora (band)|Angora]] , [[Union (band)|Union]] and [[Eric Singer Project|ESP]] (both with former [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] lead guitarist [[Bruce Kulick]]), [[Ratt]] (as a guitarist), Twenty 4 Seven (with his then Ratt bandmate [[Bobby Blotzer]]), Zen Lunatic, [[Brides of Destruction]], and Angel City Outlaws (with his then Ratt bandmates [[Robbie Crane]] and Bobby Blotzer, and former Ratt guitarist [[Keri Kelli]], who he replaced in Ratt). He was the lead singer for supergroup [[The Dead Daisies]].\n\n==M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce==\nAfter [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] parted ways with lead singer [[Vince Neil]] in February 1992, Corabi was hired as his replacement. Bassist [[Nikki Sixx]] and drummer [[Tommy Lee]] stated that Corabi was capable of singing anything and everything and that was the reason they chose him.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fielder Jr. |first=Gordon |date=August 20, 1994 |title=Motley Crue promises unique ending to BiCenter performance |publisher=Salina Journal |website=Newspapers.com |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19496902/motley_crue_promises_unique_performance/ |access-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> Corabi recorded the self-titled ''[[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce (album)|M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]'' album in 1994 and the EP ''[[Quaternary (EP)|Quaternary]]''. Though the music was heavier and more elaborate than the rest of the M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce catalog, it did not sell as well as previous releases from the band. Before a concert in Tucson, Arizona which had a 15,000 seat capacity, only 4,000 tickets were sold, Nikki Sixx decided to call into a Tucson area radio station and offer any fan who showed up free tickets. When only two people took Sixx up on his offer, Sixx stated he knew this version of the band was finished.<ref>{{cite web |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=March 20, 2018 |title=Flashback: Motley Crue Perform 'Home Sweet Home' With John Corabi |publisher=Rolling Stone |website=rollingstone.com |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/motley-crue-sing-home-sweet-home-with-john-corabi-not-vince-neil-w518071 |access-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> During the early stages of the writing of a new album which would become ''[[Generation Swine]]'', M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce's record label refused to provide funds to record the album unless Vince Neil was let back in the band. Rather than hiring another label, M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce acceded to the demand and by 1997, Corabi departed the band and Neil returned. Many of the songs from the early writing session were used on the album and Corabi is credited on the liner notes for co-writing some of the songs.\n\nCorabi and the rest of M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce made personal appearances at London's [[Hard Rock Cafe]] at a private party in February 1994 promoting their self-titled ''M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce'' album. The evening was also attended by many M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce competition winners who were invited into the VIP area to chat to Corabi, as well as the other 3 band members.\n\nCorabi spoke about his time with the band and his thoughts on the first record with M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce. Corabi said: \"my record was the first record that they had done that didn't go platinum, didn't make some sort of crazy noise, and everybody panicked\".<ref>{{cite web |date=March 9, 2019 |title=How John Corabi saved M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce with their 1994 hard rock album that failed |url=https://www.rawmusictv.com/article/2019/How-John-Corabi-saved-Motley-Crue-with-their-1994-hard-rock-album-that-failed |accessdate=March 9, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Corabi and his band performed at a bar and played all of the songs off of the M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce album. Weeks after the performance, Corabi stated \"The album would have made it if this was under a different band name\".\n\n==Union==\nUnion was formed from recently released musician [[Bruce Kulick]] of Kiss, John Corabi, Brent Fitz, and Jamie Hunting. John and Bruce wrote what would become the first Union album (self titled) and proceeded with a nationwide acoustic tour, to promote the album, featuring just Corabi and Kulick (both on guitar). Soon the full band went on a world tour headlining small venues in support of the Union album. The second album \"Live in the Galaxy\" was a live recording with two acoustic tracks recorded in a mobile studio. The third and final Union album, The Blue Room, was a more polished sound than the first studio CD. Union never officially called it quits (playing live shows every so often with guest drummers and bass players), but with Kulick playing along with [[Grand Funk Railroad]], Corabi playing with many bands, most notably [[Ratt]], and both members being tied up in solo projects, Union will probably never return to write new studio material.\n\n==ESP (Eric Singer Project)==\nESP also featured guitarist [[Bruce Kulick]], bassist [[Karl Cochran]], and drummer [[Eric Singer]]. [[Ace Frehley]] makes a special appearance on the Hendrix cover ''Foxy Lady''.\n\n==Twenty 4 Seven==\nTwenty 4 Seven, a collaboration with Corabi, drummer [[Bobby Blotzer]] ([[Ratt]], Contraband), and guitarist [[Rob Marcello]] (Ironhorse, Obsession, [[Danger Danger]]) recorded 10 hard rock tracks entitled ''Destination Everywhere'' (US, 2002).\n\n==Cardboard Vampyres==\nIn early 2004, Corabi joined [[Jerry Cantrell]]'s covers band Cardboard Vampyres. Also in the band were [[The Cult]] guitarist [[Billy Duffy]], The Cult bassist [[Chris Wyse]] and drummer Josh Howser.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jeckell |first=Barry A. |url=http://www.glidemagazine.com/6063/jerry-cantrell-forms-new-band-cardboard-vampyres/ |title=Jerry Cantrell Forms New Band \u2013 Cardboard Vampyres |website=Glide Magazine |date=June 18, 2004}}</ref> The band played at various venues in the United States between 2004 and 2005. They predominately played along the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.setlist.fm/setlists/cardboard-vampyres-7bd6aedc.html |title=Cardboard Vampyres Concert Setlists & Tour Dates |website=Setlist.fm |access-date=June 27, 2018}}</ref> No albums were released by the band.\n\n==Brides of Destruction==\nCorabi was featured as second guitarist on [[Brides of Destruction]]'s 2004 album ''[[Here Come the Brides (album)|Here Comes The Brides]]''. He had multiple reasons for leaving the band. One was the fact that he was told it would be an effort much like the \"M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce\" album. Secondly, he did not get along very well with [[Tracii Guns]]. He also said in an interview that \"when Nikki told me about the band, I was really into the idea of writing another CD with the heavy sound of the M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce album, but as we got more into recording, we had our drummer singing what was supposed to be the best song on the CD, when Nikki and Tracii were saying that our singer was the hot new thing, it just did not make sense to me.\"\n\n==Other projects==\nCorabi performed songs on the [[Karl Cochran]] solo album ''Voodooland \u2013 Give Me Air'' released in 2005.\n\n2005 also saw the release of the first [[Union (band)|Union]] DVD, Do Your Own Thing Live, containing two full-length concerts.\n\nUnion performed in Tokyo, Japan in January 2005 and toured Europe in November and December 2005.\n\nCorabi toured Europe with ESP in May 2005 and the USA with RATT in summer of 2005.\n \nIn February 2006, Corabi returned to Japan with ESP for live appearances and meet-and-greets with fans. ESP also performed in Australia in April 2006 for shows in Sydney and Melbourne.\n\nIn late 2006, Corabi played the last show with [[RATT]] fronted by [[Jizzy Pearl]] in [[Guadalajara, Mexico]] before the band reunited with original vocalist [[Stephen Pearcy]].\n\nCorabi contributed vocals on a song for Liberty N' Justice (a Christian group that does all-star rock albums) called \"Doubting Thomas.\" The track was released in 2007 on the \"Independence Day\" album.\n\nIn the Summer of 2007, Corabi toured with reunited RATT while on tour with [[Poison (American band)|Poison]], [[Dokken]], and [[Vains of Jenna]].\n\nIn November 2007 Corabi played 4 shows in Japan and 2 shows in Australia with Ratt while touring with [[Winger (band)|Winger]].\n\nIn December 2007, Corabi returned to Mexico City with ESP (Eric Singer Project) for one show and meet-and-greets with fans. The set included songs from Motorhead, Led Zeppelin, Kiss and other favorites.\n\nEarly in 2008, Corabi attended the MOTLEY CRUISE, a 4-day cruise in the Caribbean ('''Miami, Key West and Cozumel''', MX) including performers such as [[Vince Neil]], [[Skid Row (American band)|Skid Row]], [[Ratt]], [[Slaughter (band)|Slaughter]], [[Endeverafter]] and [[Lynam (band)|Lynam]]. On this cruise, Corabi joined [[Vince Neil]] on stage to perform \"Highway to Hell\" by [[AC/DC]]. This performance was a unique event as fans witnessed the two M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce vocalists share the same microphone. In August 2008, Corabi parted ways with Ratt in order to pursue his solo career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/95634 |title=RATT Working on New Material; Album Planned for Early 2009 |publisher=Bravewords.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-02}}</ref>\n\nCorabi makes a vocal appearance on Bruce Kulick's 2010 release \"BK3\". He covered \"Life\" by [[Siam Shade]] for the 2010 tribute album, ''[[Siam Shade Tribute]]''.\n\nFrom 2016 to 2019, Corabi was the lead vocalist for the Australian/American rock band [[The Dead Daisies]]. The band released an album, ''Burn it Down'' in 2018.\n\n==Discography==\n{{update|date=October 2015}}\n\n'''[[Angora (band)|Angora]]'''\n* Six song demo tape\n\n'''[[The Scream (band)|The Scream]]'''\n*''[[Let It Scream]]'' (1991)\n\n'''[[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]'''\n*''[[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce (album)|M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Quaternary (EP)|Quaternary]]'' EP (1994)\n*''[[Generation Swine]]'' (1997) <small>writer, uncredited vocals</small>\n*''[[Red, White & Cr\u00fce]] (2005)\n\n'''[[Eric Singer Project]]'''\n*''Lost and Spaced'' (1998)\n*''ESP'' (1999)\n*''Live in Japan'' (2007)\n*''ESP Live at the Marquee'' (2007)\n\n'''[[Union (band)|Union]]'''\n*''[[Union (Union album)|Union]]'' (1998)\n*''Live in the Galaxy'' (1999)\n*''[[The Blue Room (Album)|The Blue Room]]'' (2000)\n*''Do Your Own Thing Live Concert'' (2005)\n\n'''Twenty 4 Seven'''\n*''Destination Everywhere'' (2002)\n\n'''[[Brides of Destruction]]'''\n*''[[Here Come the Brides (album)|Here Comes the Brides]]'' (2004) <small>Uncredited guitar and writer</small>\n\n'''Voodooland'''\nAdvanced Ep (2003)\n*''Give Me Air'' (2004)\n\n'''Liberty N' Justice'''\n*''Doubting Thomas'' (2007)\n\n'''[[RATT]]'''\n*''[[Infestation (album)|Infestation]]'' (2010) <small>writer</small>\n\n'''John Corabi'''\n*''John Corabi Unplugged'' (November 2012)\n\n'''[[The Dead Daisies]]'''\n*''[[Revolucion (The Dead Daisies album)|Revoluci\u00f3n]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Make Some Noise (The Dead Daisies album)|Make Some Noise]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Burn It Down (The Dead Daisies album)]]'' (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johncorabimusic.com/home.cfm/ John Corabi's official website]\n*[http://www.ratpakrecordsamerica.com/johncorabi/ John Corabi Official Merchandise]\n\n*[https://www.facebook.com/JohnCorabiMusic/ John Corabi Official Facebook Page]\n\n{{The Dead Daisies}}\n{{Ratt}}\n{{M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce}}\n{{Union (band)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corabi, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce members]]\n[[Category:Ratt members]]\n[[Category:Eric Singer Project members]]\n[[Category:Union (band) members]]\n[[Category:The Scream (band) members]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Brides of Destruction members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Heavy metal singer and guitarist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{POV|date=March 2013}}\n{{original research|date=March 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2013}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = John Corabi\n|background = solo_singer\n|image = The Dead Daisies - Hamburg Harley Days 2017 18.jpg\n|caption = John Corabi in 2017\n|birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|4|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n|origin = \n|genre = [[Hard rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[glam metal]]\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter, singer\n|instrument = Vocals, guitar, bass\n|years_active = 1988\u2013present\n|label = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n|associated_acts = [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], [[The Scream (band)|The Scream]], [[Ratt]], [[Brides of Destruction]], [[Angora (band)|Angora]], [[Eric Singer Project|ESP]], [[Union (band)|Union]], Angel City Outlaws, Twenty 4 Seven, Cardboard Vampyres, [[The Dead Daisies]]\n| website = {{URL|johncorabi.com/}}\n\n|\n}}\n'''John Corabi''' (born April 26, 1959) is an American hard rock singer and guitarist. He was the frontman of [[The Scream (band)|The Scream]] during 1989. He was also the frontman of [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] between 1994 and 1996 during original frontman [[Vince Neil]]'s hiatus from the band.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Scream Bio \u2013 Sleaze Roxx|url=https://sleazeroxx.com/bios/the-scream-bio/}}</ref>\n\nCorabi is considered a \"rock journeyman\"<ref>{{cite web|title=John Corabi &#124; Biography & History &#124; AllMusic|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-corabi-mn0000218589/biography}}</ref> with a long list of collaborations with established acts such as [[Angora (band)|Angora]] , [[Union (band)|Union]] and [[Eric Singer Project|ESP]] (both with former [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] lead guitarist [[Bruce Kulick]]), [[Ratt]] (as a guitarist), Twenty 4 Seven (with his then Ratt bandmate [[Bobby Blotzer]]), Zen Lunatic, [[Brides of Destruction]], and Angel City Outlaws (with his then Ratt bandmates [[Robbie Crane]] and Bobby Blotzer, and former Ratt guitarist [[Keri Kelli]], who he replaced in Ratt). He was the lead singer for supergroup [[The Dead Daisies]].\n\n==M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce==\nAfter [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]] parted ways with lead singer [[Vince Neil]] in February 1992, Corabi was hired as his replacement. Bassist [[Nikki Sixx]] and drummer [[Tommy Lee]] stated that Corabi was capable of singing anything and everything and that was the reason they chose him.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fielder Jr. |first=Gordon |date=August 20, 1994 |title=Motley Crue promises unique ending to BiCenter performance |publisher=Salina Journal |website=Newspapers.com |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19496902/motley_crue_promises_unique_performance/ |access-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> Corabi recorded the self-titled ''[[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce (album)|M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]'' album in 1994 and the EP ''[[Quaternary (EP)|Quaternary]]''. Though the music was heavier and more elaborate than the rest of the M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce catalog, it did not sell as well as previous releases from the band. Before a concert in Tucson, Arizona which had a 15,000 seat capacity, only 4,000 tickets were sold, Nikki Sixx decided to call into a Tucson area radio station and offer any fan who showed up free tickets. When only two people took Sixx up on his offer, Sixx stated he knew this version of the band was finished.<ref>{{cite web |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=March 20, 2018 |title=Flashback: Motley Crue Perform 'Home Sweet Home' With John Corabi |publisher=Rolling Stone |website=rollingstone.com |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/motley-crue-sing-home-sweet-home-with-john-corabi-not-vince-neil-w518071 |access-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> During the early stages of the writing of a new album which would become ''[[Generation Swine]]'', M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce's record label refused to provide funds to record the album unless Vince Neil was let back in the band. Rather than hiring another label, M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce acceded to the demand and by 1997, Corabi departed the band and Neil returned. Many of the songs from the early writing session were used on the album and Corabi is credited on the liner notes for co-writing some of the songs.\n\nCorabi and the rest of M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce made personal appearances at London's [[Hard Rock Cafe]] at a private party in February 1994 promoting their self-titled ''M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce'' album. The evening was also attended by many M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce competition winners who were invited into the VIP area to chat to Corabi, as well as the other 3 band members.\n\nCorabi spoke about his time with the band and his thoughts on the first record with M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce. Corabi said: \"my record was the first record that they had done that didn't go platinum, didn't make some sort of crazy noise, and everybody panicked\".<ref>{{cite web |date=March 9, 2019 |title=How John Corabi saved M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce with their 1994 hard rock album that failed |url=https://www.rawmusictv.com/article/2019/How-John-Corabi-saved-Motley-Crue-with-their-1994-hard-rock-album-that-failed |accessdate=March 9, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Corabi and his band performed at a bar and played all of the songs off of the M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce album. Weeks after the performance, Corabi stated \"The album would have made it if this was under a different band name\".\n\n==Union==\nUnion was formed from recently released musician [[Bruce Kulick]] of Kiss, John Corabi, Brent Fitz, and Jamie Hunting. John and Bruce wrote what would become the first Union album (self titled) and proceeded with a nationwide acoustic tour, to promote the album, featuring just Corabi and Kulick (both on guitar). Soon the full band went on a world tour headlining small venues in support of the Union album. The second album \"Live in the Galaxy\" was a live recording with 2 acoustic tracks recorded in a mobile studio. The third and final Union album, The Blue Room, was a more polished sound than the first studio CD. Union never officially called it quits (playing live shows every so often with guest drummers and bass players), but with Kulick playing along with [[Grand Funk Railroad]], Corabi playing with many bands, most notably [[Ratt]], and both members being tied up in solo projects, Union will probably never return to write new studio material.\n\n==ESP (Eric Singer Project)==\nESP also featured guitarist [[Bruce Kulick]], bassist [[Karl Cochran]], and drummer [[Eric Singer]]. [[Ace Frehley]] makes a special appearance on the Hendrix cover ''Foxy Lady''.\n\n==Twenty 4 Seven==\nTwenty 4 Seven, a collaboration with Corabi, drummer [[Bobby Blotzer]] ([[Ratt]], Contraband), and guitarist [[Rob Marcello]] (Ironhorse, Obsession, [[Danger Danger]]) recorded 10 hard rock tracks entitled ''Destination Everywhere'' (US, 2002).\n\n==Cardboard Vampyres==\nIn early 2004, Corabi joined [[Jerry Cantrell]]'s covers band Cardboard Vampyres. Also in the band were [[The Cult]] guitarist [[Billy Duffy]], The Cult bassist [[Chris Wyse]] and drummer Josh Howser.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jeckell |first=Barry A. |url=http://www.glidemagazine.com/6063/jerry-cantrell-forms-new-band-cardboard-vampyres/ |title=Jerry Cantrell Forms New Band \u2013 Cardboard Vampyres |website=Glide Magazine |date=June 18, 2004}}</ref> The band played at various venues in the United States between 2004 and 2005. They predominately played along the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.setlist.fm/setlists/cardboard-vampyres-7bd6aedc.html |title=Cardboard Vampyres Concert Setlists & Tour Dates |website=Setlist.fm |access-date=June 27, 2018}}</ref> No albums were released by the band.\n\n==Brides of Destruction==\nCorabi was featured as second guitarist on [[Brides of Destruction]]'s 2004 album ''[[Here Come the Brides (album)|Here Comes The Brides]]''. He had multiple reasons for leaving the band. One was the fact that he was told it would be an effort much like the \"M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce\" album. Secondly, he did not get along very well with [[Tracii Guns]]. He also said in an interview that \"when Nikki told me about the band, I was really into the idea of writing another CD with the heavy sound of the M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce album, but as we got more into recording, we had our drummer singing what was supposed to be the best song on the CD, when Nikki and Tracii were saying that our singer was the hot new thing, it just did not make sense to me.\"\n\n==Other projects==\nCorabi performed songs on the [[Karl Cochran]] solo album ''Voodooland \u2013 Give Me Air'' released in 2005.\n\n2005 also saw the release of the first [[Union (band)|Union]] DVD, Do Your Own Thing Live, containing two full-length concerts.\n\nUnion performed in Tokyo, Japan in January 2005 and toured Europe in November and December 2005.\n\nCorabi toured Europe with ESP in May 2005 and the USA with RATT in summer of 2005.\n \nIn February 2006, Corabi returned to Japan with ESP for live appearances and meet-and-greets with fans. ESP also performed in Australia in April 2006 for shows in Sydney and Melbourne.\n\nIn late 2006, Corabi played the last show with [[RATT]] fronted by [[Jizzy Pearl]] in [[Guadalajara, Mexico]] before the band reunited with original vocalist [[Stephen Pearcy]].\n\nCorabi contributed vocals on a song for Liberty N' Justice (a Christian group that does all-star rock albums) called \"Doubting Thomas.\" The track was released in 2007 on the \"Independence Day\" album.\n\nIn the Summer of 2007, Corabi toured with reunited RATT while on tour with [[Poison (American band)|Poison]], [[Dokken]], and [[Vains of Jenna]].\n\nIn November 2007 Corabi played 4 shows in Japan and 2 shows in Australia with Ratt while touring with [[Winger (band)|Winger]].\n\nIn December 2007, Corabi returned to Mexico City with ESP (Eric Singer Project) for one show and meet-and-greets with fans. The set included songs from Motorhead, Led Zeppelin, Kiss and other favorites.\n\nEarly in 2008, Corabi attended the MOTLEY CRUISE, a 4-day cruise in the Caribbean ('''Miami, Key West and Cozumel''', MX) including performers such as [[Vince Neil]], [[Skid Row (American band)|Skid Row]], [[Ratt]], [[Slaughter (band)|Slaughter]], [[Endeverafter]] and [[Lynam (band)|Lynam]]. On this cruise, Corabi joined [[Vince Neil]] on stage to perform \"Highway to Hell\" by [[AC/DC]]. This performance was a unique event as fans witnessed the two M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce vocalists share the same microphone. In August 2008, Corabi parted ways with Ratt in order to pursue his solo career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/95634 |title=RATT Working on New Material; Album Planned for Early 2009 |publisher=Bravewords.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-02}}</ref>\n\nCorabi makes a vocal appearance on Bruce Kulick's 2010 release \"BK3\". He covered \"Life\" by [[Siam Shade]] for the 2010 tribute album, ''[[Siam Shade Tribute]]''.\n\nFrom 2016 to 2019, Corabi was the lead vocalist for the Australian/American rock band [[The Dead Daisies]]. The band released an album, ''Burn it Down'' in 2018.\n\n==Discography==\n{{update|date=October 2015}}\n\n'''[[Angora (band)|Angora]]'''\n* Six song demo tape\n\n'''[[The Scream (band)|The Scream]]'''\n*''[[Let It Scream]]'' (1991)\n\n'''[[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]'''\n*''[[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce (album)|M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]'' (1994)\n*''[[Quaternary (EP)|Quaternary]]'' EP (1994)\n*''[[Generation Swine]]'' (1997) <small>writer, uncredited vocals</small>\n*''[[Red, White & Cr\u00fce]] (2005)\n\n'''[[Eric Singer Project]]'''\n*''Lost and Spaced'' (1998)\n*''ESP'' (1999)\n*''Live in Japan'' (2007)\n*''ESP Live at the Marquee'' (2007)\n\n'''[[Union (band)|Union]]'''\n*''[[Union (Union album)|Union]]'' (1998)\n*''Live in the Galaxy'' (1999)\n*''[[The Blue Room (Album)|The Blue Room]]'' (2000)\n*''Do Your Own Thing Live Concert'' (2005)\n\n'''Twenty 4 Seven'''\n*''Destination Everywhere'' (2002)\n\n'''[[Brides of Destruction]]'''\n*''[[Here Come the Brides (album)|Here Comes the Brides]]'' (2004) <small>Uncredited guitar and writer</small>\n\n'''Voodooland'''\nAdvanced Ep (2003)\n*''Give Me Air'' (2004)\n\n'''Liberty N' Justice'''\n*''Doubting Thomas'' (2007)\n\n'''[[RATT]]'''\n*''[[Infestation (album)|Infestation]]'' (2010) <small>writer</small>\n\n'''John Corabi'''\n*''John Corabi Unplugged'' (November 2012)\n\n'''[[The Dead Daisies]]'''\n*''[[Revolucion (The Dead Daisies album)|Revoluci\u00f3n]]'' (2015)\n*''[[Make Some Noise (The Dead Daisies album)|Make Some Noise]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Burn It Down (The Dead Daisies album)]]'' (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johncorabimusic.com/home.cfm/ John Corabi's official website]\n*[http://www.ratpakrecordsamerica.com/johncorabi/ John Corabi Official Merchandise]\n\n*[https://www.facebook.com/JohnCorabiMusic/ John Corabi Official Facebook Page]\n\n{{The Dead Daisies}}\n{{Ratt}}\n{{M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce}}\n{{Union (band)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corabi, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce members]]\n[[Category:Ratt members]]\n[[Category:Eric Singer Project members]]\n[[Category:Union (band) members]]\n[[Category:The Scream (band) members]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Brides of Destruction members]]\n", "name_user": "Koavf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Corabi"}
